JOHANNESBURG - Transport Minister, Blade Nzimande, has appointed a new board for the embattled Passenger Rail Agency of South Africa (Prasa). Khanyisile Kweyama will serve as chairperson for 12 months. He served as interim board chairperson at the SABC after the axing of the public broadcaster's former COO, Hlaudi Motsoeneng. Dr Simo Lushaba has been appointed as acting CEO of Prasa. READ: Prasa chairperson resigns The minister hopes the appointments will change the state of paralysis at the agency. "This board is carefully selected on the basis of skills and expertise required to run a company of this magnitude. Their skills set include amongst others the technical, corporate governance, legal, finance, risk management and human resources. READ:Â Prasa denies VBS investments deal reports "As the shareholder, I ensured that only people with expertise, experience and integrity serve in these vital positions," Nzimande said in a statement on Friday. Prasa has been dogged by various problems including train delays and cancellations which have affected the local economy, vandalism and attacks on staff, as well as various scandals regarding the procurement of new locomotives. eNCA